Billboard has a flashy new UI, and that change broke this module.

This is the beginning of a fix for it: as of right now, this has basic function for everything EXCEPT the artist charts. I will look into that tomorrow.  Also, as of right now, this code has been geared completely for functionality and elegance/style has been more or less ignored. Please comment away and I will modify the PR when I return to my computer.

@guoguo12 , would it be possible to merge this fix and deploy to PyPI so that there is at least limited functionality while I complete the fix? This is blocking me on another project.

In some cases, it's useful to store the dirty fields as an audit in various storage mechanisms such as a postgres jsonb column. Some values will not serialise to JSON and this PR allows the client to supply a function that will normalise the values into a format that can be serialised. 

```
import datetime
    from django.db import models
    from dirtyfields import DirtyFieldsMixin

    def your_normalise_function(value):
        if isinstance(value, (datetime.datetime, datetime.date)):
            return value.isoformat()
        else:
            return value

    class TestModel(DirtyFieldsMixin, models.Model):
        normalise_function = (your_normalise_function, {'extra_kwargs': 1})

```

Sometimes after Create or Login an user (base on Token) we need some information about he/she, so after receive the token we need to request again the server.

Example: 
When we send the email and password Flask-Security returns:
{
    "meta": {
        "code": 200
    },
    "response": {
        "user": {
            "authentication_token": "WyI5OTk5OTk5IiwiMTE0ODZlNzU3MGNjNWRkMjFiZDhkMzI4M2I5ZTUxZjYiXQ.C39mEg.UGm6QqOaGlZ3wJsu5jQuWaIIA8M",
            "id": "9999999"
        }
    }
}

Is really good. But if we need more information we should request the server again.

I introduced a new setting flag called SECURITY_CUSTOM_USER_PAYLOAD. By default is False.
If you set to True, you must define a function in your User Model called 'payload_handler' that must return a serializable object:

UserModel(Base):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
    email = db.Column(db.String(120), unique=True, nullable=False)
    password = db.Column(db.String(255))
    name = db.Column(db.String(80))
    
    def payload_handler(self):
        return {
            id: self.id,
            name: self.name,
            email: self.email  
        }

Now after login the user the response is:

{
    "meta": {
        "code": 200
    },
    "response": {
        "user": {
            "authentication_token": "WyI5OTk5OTk5IiwiMTE0ODZlNzU3MGNjNWRkMjFiZDhkMzI4M2I5ZTUxZjYiXQ.C39maw.EYNyKu2-T70BJFyWlFiMsjWh-XA",
            "email": "test@tes.com",
            "id": 9999999,
            "name": "test",
        }
    }
}

An alternate version of zip() that can be used a bit more like python's version, and runs a bit faster.
```perl
use strict;
use warnings;
use Benchmark;
use AI::MXNet 'mx';

my @l1 = (0 .. 64);
my @l2 = (0 .. 64);
my @l3 = (0 .. 64);
my @l4 = (0 .. 64);

sub orig_zip
{
    my ($sub, @arrays) = @_;
    my $len = @{ $arrays[0] };
    for (my $i = 0; $i < $len; $i++)
    {
        $sub->(map { $_->[$i] } @arrays);
    }
}

Benchmark::cmpthese(-4, {
    orig => sub {
        my @l;
        orig_zip(sub {
            push @l, $_[0] + $_[1] + $_[2] + $_[3];
        }, \@l1, \@l2, \@l3, \@l4);
    },
    repl => sub {
        my @l;
        AI::MXNet::zip(sub {
            push @l, $_[0] + $_[1] + $_[2] + $_[3];
        }, \@l1, \@l2, \@l3, \@l4);
    },
    pure => sub {
        my @l = map { $_->[0] + $_->[1] + $_->[2] + $_->[3] }
            AI::MXNet::zip(\@l1, \@l2, \@l3, \@l4);
    },
});
```
gives

|    |   Rate|orig|repl|pure|
|----|-------|----|----|----|
|orig|21964/s|  --|-32%|-37%|
|repl|32190/s| 47%|  --| -7%|
|pure|34657/s| 58%|  8%|  --|

